{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505277"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.03,0.14,0.21,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93369"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35926"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of increasing pain and swelling in her right leg. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has a pet rainbow lorikeet that occasionally nibbles her skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe visited her General Practitioner four days ago and was prescribed oral cephalexin, but the swelling and redness have worsened despite treatment. She reports subjective fevers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 146/98 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. The right leg is erythematous and swollen from the ankle to mid-thigh, with a 1 cm superficial ulceration on the medial calf. The affected area is tense and very tender to touch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous flucloxacillin","Oral phenoxymethylpenicillin","Intravenous benzylpenicillin","Intravenous vancomycin","Oral dicloxacillin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cellulitis that has failed oral antibiotic therapy and shows signs of systemic infection (fever, tachycardia). The presence of a penetrating injury from bird bites increases the risk of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it provides excellent coverage against methicillin-sensitive \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MSSA), which is the most likely pathogen. The intravenous route is necessary due to treatment failure with oral antibiotics and systemic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral phenoxymethylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate as it has poor activity against \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E and oral therapy has already failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E also has poor activity against \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E and would be an inappropriate choice for presumed staphylococcal cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were risk factors for methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA), such as previous MRSA infection or recent hospitalisation, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral dicloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as oral therapy has already failed and the patient requires intravenous treatment due to systemic features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cellulitis that is worsening despite oral antibiotics or has systemic features requires intravenous therapy.","Flucloxacillin is first-line therapy for presumed Staphylococcus aureus cellulitis in patients without risk factors for methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA).","Animal bites or scratches increase the risk of Staphylococcus aureus infection."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Cellulitis and erysipelas. Victoria: eTG; 2019 [cited 2021 Feb 24]. Available from: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=cellulitis-erysipelas\u0026sectionId=abg16-c130-s8#toc_d1e47.","Brindle R, Williams M, Barton E. Assessment of Antibiotic Treatment of Cellulitis and Erysipelas: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. JAMA Dermatology. 2019; 155;(9): 1033-1040. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31188407/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93369"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93369"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-11T19:10:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T19:11:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111237"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud